{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_eridanus_ver02/data/sn89053204/00393343655/1923111301/0388.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE SIX\nTIMES-RECORDER\ni*T9\nPublished by\nThe Times-Recorder Co., (Inc.)\nLovelace Eve, '\"ditor and Publisher\nlatand at MCQnJ ct\u00abM nailer at the pvitoftiee\nat AJnerkua, Georgia, according tw the Act of\nCoafreee.\nThe Amo ci a ted Prew ta aacluaitelT entitled to\n(be uee for rhe republication of all \u00ab<**a die\n(\u00abat<Mva red it <4 to it or not otherwiee credited to\nrLra paper mt-lrhe local noww published here\nto. All right of tcpeblicaiion of epeetel diapaftebea\nere alao reserved.\nNational Advertising Repreeeotathree, FROST\nMFWS A KOHN, Brunswick Bldg.. New York;\nPeoples* Gas Bldg.. Chicago\nA Thought\nEvery man according as he pur\nposeth in his heart, so let him\ngive; not grudgingly, or of neces\nsity; for God loveth a cheerful\ngiver.\u2014Cor. 9:7.\nPosthumous charities are the\nvery essence of selfishness, when\nbequeathed by those who, when\nalive would part with nothing.\nCotton.\nA Banker\u2019s Viewpoint\nHere\u2019s good sound advice car\nried in an advertisement by the\nExchange National Bank of Fitz\ngerald.\nIt is interesting to both farmer\nand merchant, because of the bene\nfit* that will fillow to those who\nfollow the advice of the banker.\nThe advertisement follows:\n\u201cIt is wonderful how some sec\ntions in Georgia came back in\nfine shape this year after they\nhad been on the verge of finan\ncial ruin for two or three years\nbefore from ravages of boll wee\nvil, making enough cotton this\nyear by reduced acreage, poison\ning and reasonable weather to\nmove baek towards easy street,\nhaving received good prices.\n\u201cThis brnk has never lost faith\nin this section here.\n\u201cOur bank is firmly planted\nand we look for great prosperity\nand the return of values in due\nseason.\n\u201cWith normal weather another\nyear, cotton acreage reduced,\nreasonable acreage put into pea\nnuts for market, with our farm\ners supplying our creamery, with\nthousands of hens laping and\ndozens of earloads of poultry\nshipped ds the poultry business\nincreases since our great hatch\nery i s in, with hundreds of acres\ngrowing tobacco, (with a large\nnumber of thrifty farmers sell\ning carrots, b<Kts, cucumbers and\nin carload: Ms, growing abund-\nWEEK OF THE YEAR\u2014who\ncan keen baek bappiijpas apd pros\nperity but the people them\nselves?\u201d\nThe whole story is that the far\nmer who diversifies has cash com\ning in evc in the year. Com\npare his lose as fthe Kn\u2019ff of'the sbh\nson with the fellow who raised\nnothing buticoUon. I\nOs courw we must have cotton,\nbut not too much cotton. Living\nat home is or should be considered\nfirst.\nConstructive News\nThe publishers of Georgia news\npapers are emphasizing the impor\ntance of devoting more of their\nspace to what may be called \u201ccon\nstructive news.\u201d\n\u201cThere is no doubt that capital\nfrom various parts of the country\nis being attracted to the South and\nthat citizens of distant states are\nawakened to the great opportuni\nties in this and other southern\nstates,\u201d said one Atlanta editor.\n\u2018The newspapers will contribute to\nthis progress to a great extent if\nthey will make it a policy to fea\nture the constructive news of theii\nsections.\"\n\u2022Showing what our farmers are\niccomplishhig; what individual\nGeorgians are performing in the\nitate; what the corporations are do\ning; all these help to call atten\ntion to the vast undeveloped re\nsources of the state.\nThere was never a time when the\npapers of the state were devoting\nmore space than today in an effoit\nto show what can be produced on\nGeorgia soil.\nCommunism\nAfter annulling the charter oi\nradical laborites at Seattle, the na\ntional convention of the Americm\nfederation of Labor at Portland\nput the brand ol rejection upon\nRed Communism.\nIt s most pronounced western ex\nponent, William F. Dvnne, was\nkicked out when the convention\ndelegates, l.y alsot unanimous vote\nunseated the Butte man because of\nhis red activities. Matthew Wolt,\nvice -president of the Federation\nsayrf:\nThe American Federation of\nLabor was acting on a much\nlarger case when Dunne was un\nseated.\n\".Dunne by himself was not\nimportant enough to justify the\n.the day of debate and the mak\ning oi a national issue.\n\"What the convention did wa\nto throw out the thing foi\nwhich Dunne stands as one of its\nhalf-dozet) most prominent ex\nponents hi America.\n\u201cThe American labor move\nment threw out the last race of\n1 voloUo-jrry dogma. the\ntrace of, Hostility to consttfm\nti'\u2014 d method. I\n-\u00bbnde the i\u201c B ue when he\nI'e-'-'-ort for communism hv rev\nolutionary means, for diefiance\nS\nto the constitution, forth\n_ whole Russian program. He made\nit impossible for a democratic\ntrade unici movement to tol\ni j erate his presence.\u201d\nL\nBusiness Outlook\nThe business outlook is good, ac\ncording to Jesse L. Livermore,\nknown in Wall Street as the larg\nest individual stock market opera-\ntor. Livermore says:\n\u201cDuring the past few years the\npeople of our country have be\ncome accustomed to living on a\nhigher standard than heretofore,\nand they are not going to be sat\nisfied to live any other way in the\nfuture. The money they spend\nmust necessarily mean a larger\nI purchasing power, and that pur\nchasing power is bound to keep\nbusiness going at a good' volume.\u201d\nLivermore is right. Thrift\u2014the\ni savings instinct\u2014is a fine thing.\nBut spending makes prosperity. Foe\ninstance, people have become ac\ncustomed to buying autos. This\nbuying makes jobs for the army\nof people engaged in manufactur\ning the cars.\nIn turn, these car makers spend\nthe money they receive thus keep\ning busy the employes in other in\ndustries. The more we spend for\n'egitimate purposes of production,\nthe more jobs there are\u2014and\nthe more prosperity to be divided\namong all of us.\nCommon sense, of course, shows\nus that when a man makes more and\nspends more, he also should save\nmore.\nWe can\u2019t have luxuries and nec\nessities unless we create them. It's\nplain that we have to produce more\nif we want to have more. Larger\nproduction is the price of higher\nstandard of living. And the stan\ndard of living is flexible\u2014it moves\nup or down, accordingly as we pro\nduce more commidities or not.\nHumanity can\u2019t consume more\nthan it produces. The ravens don't\nbring manna in our generation.\nOPINIONS OF\nOTHER EDITORS\nFAR FROM BROKE\nEstimates of-the value of \u20ac\u00bbeor\ngia hapvgsts for 1923 range\nafountr 1)00,000. This is ap\nproximatelv more\nthan for.the preceding year- and\n$67,000,000 above 1921. Food\ncrops have played a big\npart ii bringing this au\ntumn\u2019s income. While the cot\nton -n-reage Okceeded that of last\nyerp- by about 8 per cent there\nwas a more marked increase i i\nboth the extent and the diversity\nof planting that goes to fill thte\nlarder.\u2014Dawson News.\nLET\u2019S CHANGE THIS.\nWe are heartily in accord with\nthe following from the LaGrange\nGraphic, which says: \u201cThe South,\nthe richest industrial part of the\nworld, too long has been content\nto produce her raw materials and\nship them into other parts of the\ncot 'try to be manufactured or\ndeveloped. By manufacturing\nthese materials at the source of\norigin, we not only receive the\nmanifold Increase in the selling\nprice of the m nufactured prod\nuct over the raw material, but\nhave all the wages of labor,\nskilled and unskilled, which is\nkept at home for further de\nvelopment and manufacture.\u201d\nONLY PURE BRED CATTLE\nWe warn you, Mr. Dairy Man,\nput away the scrub sire. You\nneed grade cattle that will pro\nduce more and more and more\nbutter tat. To have them you\nmust increase your herds with\nonly selected pure bred sires.\nYou cannot do this back breed\ning. You will lose thousands\nand thousands of dollars doing\nthat. And when you have a cow\nto sell, you can sell a good one.\nPretty soon there will be dairy\nmen here making good money\nselling their creditably developed\ndairy cattle which have raised\nthemselves througn the right\nsource. The c operut ve pure\nbull organ tion in' Crisp coun\nty can h. ve a tremendous mean\ning t- you. Better study it\u2014Cor\ndele Dispatch.\nPROFESSIONAL FOOTBALL\nThere is fear in some quarters\nthat tootball will degenerate intv\n-i professional game. Instances\ngiven of amateurs being induced\nto inter professional games un\nder an assumed name.\nNot tootball is popular be\ncause it is played by college men\nor school men and professional\nfootball, as the New York World\nu d l n haidly gain so strong\na hold. The present rules for\nfootball call for the utmost dis\npute o f physicial courage and\nstamma and big fees will hardly\nhelp the matter. The amateur\nlight tg for his alma mater meas\nures up to the ultimate test of a\nfoot ba I game. Professionals\nmay play the game beautifully\nmay even carry college inspira\ntion, but it earnot endure long.\nSo long as tootbail requires\nthe utmost of its mm, even\nthrowing a tiring and wounded\nplajer into a situation where\nhe must toss the last of his vital-'\nit> m the superb rush, the game\n\u2022annot reach its higheM pitch as\na professional sport.\nM hojs goi ri g to see'crowd of\n,n'\u2019n.> nd l ,rot \u2018ssionals tfay\ndesf b md\u2019 t A n P, a rugb v is !,ot\nIc..t led tv become contaminated.\n\u2014bavannah Pr>B\u00df,\nM's.S Daily Poem' B tton r e\na\u2014\nRETAIN YOUR CLOTHING\nThe man who keeps his shirt on\nIs the fellow who is wise,\nHe\u2019ll get long for certain\nBetter than hasty guys.\nWhen there\u2019s nny trouble brewing\nHe\u2019ll be safer than the wight\nWho gets red of eye and stewing,\nAnd who\u2019s spoiling for a fight.\nThe man who keeps his shirt on\nMay, at seasons, have to scrap,\nThere are things you can\u2019t avert on\nSome occasions; but the chap\nWho, though angry keeps his bal-\nance\nAnd i s calm throughout the fray\nCan use all his fighting talents\nin the most effective way.\nAnd in ordinary cases\nAnd the steady run of life,\nHe who keeps his temper faces\nVery little storm or strife;\nAnd 1 venture to assert on\nMost occasions which I note,\nThat the man who keeps his shirt on\nSeldom has to shed his coat!\nu y\nOLD DAIS D\\ AMERICAS\nm .U,\nTEN YEARS AGO TODAY\n(From the Times-Recorder. Nov.\n13, 1913.)\nRepresentatives of the Americus\nPower Co., and of the Americus\ncouncil, are in New York todap\n\u2019n conference with the holders of\nsecurities of the Americus Gas\nElectric Co., relative to the pro\nposed consolidation of interests of\nthe two electric lighting and pow\ner plants in Americus, a proposi\ntion discussed for some time here.\n,ri wedding on Wednesday eve\nning of Miss Lula Bacon and Mr.\nJoseph C. Kircher, of Albuquerque,\nNew Mexico, was one of the Jovli\nest social affairs of the season, oc\ncurring at the home of the bride\u2019s\nsister, Mrs. Ed Sheffield, on\nChurch street.\nThe most successful sale of the\nAmericus realty and one in its re\nsults reflecting iwiUes here and\nwonderful development as well\nwas that of the Hooks Andrews\nsub-divisicn of the James Ansley\nproperty yesterday afternoon. Fifty\nresidence lots beautifully situated J\nwere sold within the brief time of\nminutes by the Carolina Develop\nment Co.\nMr. and Mrs. George W. Riley re\nturned yesterday from Atlanta\nwhere they attended the recent au-,\ntomobile show, visiting friends in\nMacon for a day while en route I\nhome. i\nTWENTY YEARS AGO TODAY\n(From the Times-Recorder. Nov.\n13, 1903.)\nWill Hawkes, the little son of i\nCity Clerk, T. N. Hawkes, received j\na sever fall yesterday, breaking his j\narm. The injury was a very pain\nful one.\nA handsome young passenger\nwas sidetracked yesterday at the 1\nhome of Engineer J. R. Bird. May I\nhe yet be the Seaboards president, j\nMrs. W. J. Josey has returned I\nfrom a visit to relatives in At-\nlanta, her former home.\nRennie Mae and India Bell Crit-1\ntendon of Shellman two of Geor-|\ngia\u2019s fairest belles are guests of\nTHE REFEREE\nYOUTH\nThis ad caught our eye in the\nAmerican Boy: \"Join our Boys Av\nation Club. It costs one dollar.\n1 his entitles you to receive all the\nmaterial, silk wkrg covering, plans\nand all for constructing a model\nglider, also entitles you to enter\nyour completed model in the\ngreatest Boys Model airplan con\ntest.\u201d\nWe are not yet bald-headed, but\nifter reading this ad we are won\nlering how many years we are be\nmid the times. This new genera\ncion that s rising- speaks a strange\nlanguage.\n\nGAMBLING\nNever a shortage of moths for\n.lying into the candle flame. In tho\nfirst 10 months this year, over 190\nmillion shares of stocks changed\n.lands cn the New York Exchange.\nIn the corresponding months oi\n1901, sales totaled over 230 mil\nlion shares. And the average since\n1900 has been IGO millions\u2019for the\nsame months.\nLike all gambling, it\u2019s run on the\nlaw of averages. And the suckers\ncome along, year after year, by\nthe same law.\n\nVALENTINO\n\"I have only 1.50 suits of clothes,\u2019\nays Rudolph Valentino sadly. \"You\nnay think that a large number, but\nclothes to me are just like a pick\n:nd shovel to a laborer\u2014thev are\nI my tools.\u201d\nEven Socrates would listen to\nthat,\nSoi rates also would be keenly in\nterested in the bit of cable uewa\nlesci ibing Valentino in his boudoir,\n\"several French, journalists inter\nviewing him on international re.'-:-\ntions.\" The teal joke about this is\nthat some of the politicians who\nactually shape \u201cinternational rela\ntions aren\u2019t half as keen and wise\nas the Shiek.\nTAX\nIf your income this year is large\nenough lor Uncle Sam\u2019s income tax\nbut not over SSOOO, the tax blank\nyou\u2019ll have to fill out will be a sin\ngle sheet instead of the former si<-\npage document. Directions will be\nsimpler and clearer, the Interna)\nRevenue Bureau promises the four\n.n-.i)jion who\u2019ll use,.the form.\nSimpler forms are k. The'\nincome tax law should also be sim\nplified. Drawn up by lawyers, it\u2019s\nso complicated it has made work\nfor nearly the vyho|\u00a3 legal profes\nsion of our laws.\nTHE AMERICUS riMES-RECORDER\ntheir sister, Mrs. W. T. Lane.\nIn celebration of a happy birth\nday anniversary Mr. and Mrs. John\nT. Taylor entertained very delight\nfully last evening at their beauti\nful home on Lee. street. Near rela\ntives only constituted the list of in\nvited guests and this \u201cfamily circle\u2019\nwas indeed a charming one as was\nthe occasion, all wishing for the\nfair hostess and genial host many\nh ippy returns of this anniversary\ndate.\nAs suddenly as it went down the\nday before, the cotton market went\nup again yesterday, closing weil\nabove the eleven cents mark. Jan\nuary climbed to 11.00 a gain of a\ndozen points, and not a few here\nwho \u201cheld i contract\u201d felt gratly\nrelieved at the course of the mar\nket. Spot cotton sold in Americus\nat 10 3-8 cents easily.\nTHIRTY YEARS AGO TODAY\n(From the Times-Recorder. Nov.\n13, 1893.)\nCarrier, the six-year-old daugh\nter of Mr. and Mrs. J. A. Pinkston\ndied Sunday evening after a shoe,\nillness from diptheria. The little\nwas sick onlv a few days, but\nthe of the best medical\nskill were-powerless to stay the\ndreaded disease.\nWill Glover was serving oysters\non the half shell up to 1:20 o\u2019clock\nSaturday night at \u201cThe Windsor\nCase\u201d If the ladies want tempting\nrefreshments Glover Horne\u2019s is\nthe place to go.\nA \u2018\u2019-'w plain drunks and a couple\nof \"knock down arid drag out\u201d\nfights graced the docket When May\nor Cutts called the court to order\nyesterday. The drunks were\nquickly settled while the record of\nthe belligerents will be investigat\ned this mornings\nMiss Carrie Speer left yesterday\nfor Macon, -where she will be the\nguest of her cousin, Miss Rosa Me\nrary, for a week or so.\nMr. Wm. Littleton, an old Amer\nicus boy, who is now conducting l\nlarge lumber business near Albany\nwas in the city for a short time yes\nterday.\nLATER\nPublication of Steinmetz\u2019s will n\nnews public amazement at tin\nsmallness of his fortune. He couli,\nhave commanded a fabulous incoim\nyet all he wanted was enough t<\nlive on. He worked hard, but so.\nhumanity instead of himself.\nDifficult for our greedy individ\nualistic generation to understand\nhim. The Steinmetz way will b<\nthe rule, rather thr.r the xception\nin some future generation of real\nly ei -ilized men. How many scores\not generations hence?\n>h\nNEW YORK\nIn 192-1 it cost, roughly, 124 mil\nlion dollars tp run the city govern\nment ol New T ork. The budget\nlor 1924 is over 375 million. This\ni is only 188 million in terms of 1914\nlor the dollars\u2019 buying power is\nabout half what it was in 1914.\nGovernment has to pay more fm\nwhat it gets, same as the rest oi\nus.\nAll the more reason for economy.\nDebts contracted by government\nnow may be paid off later when a\ncyclic period of lower prices may\nmake the dollar worth twice as\nmuch as now. Did it ever occurr to\nI you that a general return to pre\nwar prices would in effect dou-\nble our national, city and state\ndebts?\n\u25a0I BUENA VISTA I\nMr. and Mrs. L. H. Bethume,\n1 Mrs. E. B. Reese, Mr. and Mrs. R.\n1 1. Stevens, Mj ss Elizabeth Mc-\nLiv l 'iv n<l ssra Arthur Guy and\n'f7-\u00b0' ve s PUit last Tuesday in\nI Columbus.\nz rs M. Clements, Mrs. F. L I\nClements, Mrs. 1.. H. Bethume'\nI ar y Bailey Clements and\nI Mr. h. M. Clements spent last Fri-\nday in t.olumbus,\ni t rs -_ Nannie Kinchen and Miss i\nLucretia Bullock has returned\nI\"\u00b0\u2122 a Pleasant visit to Mr. O. C.\nBullock in Columbus.\nMessrs, J. C. Butt, Jr., and X.\ni m kt 3 of the Georgia Tech;\njam Mr. .Norman Chapman of At\n\u25a0llant-i spent the week-end at homo.\n-His. B. L. Rainey spent' the\nweek-end in Ellaville